R and RStudio
========================================================

### What is R?
[R](http://r-project.org/) is a language and environment for statistical computing and graphics developed in 1993. It provides a wide variety of statistical and graphical techniques (linear and nonlinear modeling, statistical tests, time series analysis, classification, clustering, ...), and is highly extensible, meaning that the user community can write new R tools. It is a GNU project (Free and Open Source).

The R language has its roots in the S language and environment which was developed at Bell Laboratories (formerly AT&T, now Lucent Technologies) by John Chambers and colleagues. R was created by Ross Ihaka and Robert Gentleman at the University of Auckland, New Zealand, and now, R is developed by the R Development Core Team, of which Chambers is a member. R is named partly after the first names of the first two R authors (Robert Gentleman and Ross Ihaka), and partly as a play on the name of S. R can be considered as a different implementation of S. There are some important differences, but much code written for S runs unaltered under R.

Some of R's strengths:

* The ease with which well-designed publication-quality plots can be produced, including mathematical symbols and formulae where needed. Great care has been taken over the defaults for the minor design choices in graphics, but the user retains full control. Such as examples like the following (extracted from http://web.stanford.edu/class/bios221/book/Chap-Graphics.html):

<img src="chap3-rgraphics-heatmap-1.png" width="32%" /><img src="chap3-rgraphics-darned1-1.png" width="32%" /><img src="chap3-rgraphics-twodsp4-1.png" width="32%" />

* It compiles and runs on a wide variety of UNIX platforms and similar systems (including FreeBSD and Linux), Windows and MacOS.
* R can be extended (easily) via packages.
* R has its own LaTeX-like documentation format, which is used to supply comprehensive documentation, both on-line in a number of formats and in hardcopy.
* It has a vast community both in academia and in business.
* It's FREE!   

### The R environment
R is an integrated suite of software facilities for data manipulation, calculation and graphical display. It includes

* an effective data handling and storage facility,
* a suite of operators for calculations on arrays, in particular matrices,
* a large, coherent, integrated collection of intermediate tools for data analysis,
* graphical facilities for data analysis and display either on-screen or on hardcopy, and
* a well-developed, and effective programming language which includes conditionals, loops, user-defined recursive functions and input and output facilities.

The term "environment" is intended to characterize it as a fully planned and coherent system, rather than an incremental accretion of very specific and inflexible tools, as is frequently the case with other data analysis software.

R, like S, is designed around a true computer language, and it allows users to add additional functionality by defining new functions. Much of the system is itself written in the R dialect of S, which makes it easy for users to follow the algorithmic choices made. For computationally-intensive tasks, C, C++ and Fortran code can be linked and called at run time. Advanced users can write C code to manipulate R objects directly.

Many users think of R as a statistics system. The R group prefers to think of it of an environment within which statistical techniques are implemented.   

### The R Homepage
The R homepage has a wealth of information on it,

[R-project.org](http://r-project.org/)

On the homepage you can:

* Learn more about R
* Download R
* Get Documentation (official and user supplied)
* Get access to CRAN 'Comprehensive R archival network'

### Interface for R

There are many ways one can interface with R language. Here are a few popular ones:

* [RStudio](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ucdavis-bioinformatics-training/2019-March-Bioinformatics-Prerequisites/master/wednesday/Intro2R/rstudio.png)
* [RGui](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ucdavis-bioinformatics-training/2019-March-Bioinformatics-Prerequisites/master/wednesday/Intro2R/rgui.png)
* Jupyter and R notebooks
* text editors, such as vi(m), Emacs...


### RStudio

[RStudio](http://rstudio.com/) started in 2010, to offer R a more full featured integrated development environment (IDE) and modeled after matlab's IDE.

RStudio has many features:

* syntax highlighting
* code completion
* smart indentation
* "Projects"
* workspace browser and data viewer
* embedded plots
* Markdown notebooks, Sweave authoring and knitr with one click pdf or html
* runs on all platforms and over the web
* etc. etc. etc.

RStudio and its team have contributed to many R packages.[13] These include:

* Tidyverse – R packages for data science, including ggplot2, dplyr, tidyr, and purrr
* Shiny – An interactive web technology
* RMarkdown – Insert R code into markdown documents
* knitr – Dynamic reports combining R, TeX, Markdown & HTML
* packrat – Package dependency tool
* devtools – Package development tool

RStudio Cheat Sheets: [rstudio-ide.pdf](https://github.com/rstudio/cheatsheets/raw/master/rstudio-ide.pdf)

Programming fundamentals
====================================================


There are three concepts that are essential in any programming language:

* <font color='purple'>VARIABLES</font>

A variable is a named storage. Creating a variable is to reserve some space in memory. In R, the name of a variable can have letters, numbers, dot and underscore. However, a valid variable name cannot start with a underscore or a number, or start with a dot that is followed by a number.


* <font color='purple'>FUNCTIONS</font>

A function is a block of organized, reusable code that is used to perform a set of predefined operations. A function may take zero or more parameters and return a result.

<img src="./func.png" width="15%" style="display: block; margin: auto;" />


The way to use a function in R is:

**function.name(parameter1=value1, ...)**

In R, to get help information on a funciton, one may use the command: 

**?function.name**


* <font color='purple'>OPERATIONS</font>

<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };

    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

<script>
function buildQuiz(myq, qc){
  // variable to store the HTML output
  const output = [];

  // for each question...
  myq.forEach(
    (currentQuestion, questionNumber) => {

      // variable to store the list of possible answers
      const answers = [];

      // and for each available answer...
      for(letter in currentQuestion.answers){

        // ...add an HTML radio button
        answers.push(
          `<label>
            <input type="radio" name="question${questionNumber}" value="${letter}">
            ${letter} :
            ${currentQuestion.answers[letter]}
          </label><br/>`
        );
      }

      // add this question and its answers to the output
      output.push(
        `<div class="question"> ${currentQuestion.question} </div>
        <div class="answers"> ${answers.join('')} </div><br/>`
      );
    }
  );

  // finally combine our output list into one string of HTML and put it on the page
  qc.innerHTML = output.join('');
}

function showResults(myq, qc, rc){

  // gather answer containers from our quiz
  const answerContainers = qc.querySelectorAll('.answers');

  // keep track of user's answers
  let numCorrect = 0;

  // for each question...
  myq.forEach( (currentQuestion, questionNumber) => {

    // find selected answer
    const answerContainer = answerContainers[questionNumber];
    const selector = `input[name=question${questionNumber}]:checked`;
    const userAnswer = (answerContainer.querySelector(selector) || {}).value;

    // if answer is correct
    if(userAnswer === currentQuestion.correctAnswer){
      // add to the number of correct answers
      numCorrect++;

      // color the answers green
      answerContainers[questionNumber].style.color = 'lightgreen';
    }
    // if answer is wrong or blank
    else{
      // color the answers red
      answerContainers[questionNumber].style.color = 'red';
    }
  });

  // show number of correct answers out of total
  rc.innerHTML = `${numCorrect} out of ${myq.length}`;
}
</script>

<div id="there-are-5-basic-atomic-classes-numeric-integer-complex-character-logical" class="section level4">
<h4>There are 5 basic atomic classes: numeric (integer, complex), character, logical</h4>
<div id="examples-of-numeric-values." class="section level5">
<h5>Examples of numeric values.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign number 150 to variable a.
a &lt;- 150
a</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 150</code></pre>

b &lt;- 3e-2
b</code></pre>

<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="examples-of-character-values." class="section level5">
<h5>Examples of character values.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign a string &quot;BRCA1&quot; to variable gene
gene &lt;- &quot;BRCA1&quot;
gene</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;BRCA1&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign a string &quot;Hello World&quot; to variable hello
hello &lt;- &quot;Hello World&quot;
hello</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Hello World&quot;</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="examples-of-logical-values." class="section level5">
<h5>Examples of logical values.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign logical value &quot;TRUE&quot; to variable brca1_expressed
brca1_expressed &lt;- TRUE
brca1_expressed</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign logical value &quot;FALSE&quot; to variable her2_expressed
her2_expressed &lt;- FALSE
her2_expressed</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign logical value to a variable by logical operation
her2_expression_level &lt;- 0
her2_expressed &lt;- her2_expression_level &gt; 0
her2_expressed</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="to-find-out-the-type-of-variable." class="section level5">
<h5>To find out the type of variable.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>class(her2_expressed)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;logical&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># To check whether the variable is a specific type
is.numeric(gene)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>is.numeric(a)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>is.character(gene)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="in-the-case-that-one-compares-two-different-classes-of-data-the-coersion-rule-in-r-is-logical---integer---numeric---complex---character-.-the-following-is-an-example-of-converting-a-numeric-variable-to-character." class="section level5">
<h5>In the case that one compares two different classes of data, the coersion rule in R is <font color="red">logical -&gt; integer -&gt; numeric -&gt; complex -&gt; character</font> . The following is an example of converting a numeric variable to character.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>b</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 0.03</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>as.character(b)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;0.03&quot;</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
<p>What happens when one converts a logical variable to numeric?</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># recall her2_expressed
her2_expressed</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># conversion
as.numeric(her2_expressed)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 0</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>her2_expressed + 1</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="a-logical-true-is-converted-to-integer-1-and-a-logical-false-is-converted-to-integer-0." class="section level5">
<h5>A logical <em>TRUE</em> is converted to integer 1 and a logical <em>FALSE</em> is converted to integer 0.</h5>

<div id="atomic-vectors-an-atomic-vector-is-a-combination-of-multiple-valuesnumeric-character-or-logical-in-the-same-object.-an-atomic-vector-is-created-using-the-function-c." class="section level4">
<h4>Atomic vectors: an atomic vector is a combination of multiple values(numeric, character or logical) in the same object. An atomic vector is created using the function c().</h4>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names &lt;- c(&quot;ESR1&quot;, &quot;p53&quot;, &quot;PI3K&quot;, &quot;BRCA1&quot;, &quot;EGFR&quot;)
gene_names</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot;  &quot;p53&quot;   &quot;PI3K&quot;  &quot;BRCA1&quot; &quot;EGFR&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_expression &lt;- c(0, 100, 50, 200, 80)
gene_expression</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]   0 100  50 200  80</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
<div id="one-can-give-names-to-the-elements-of-an-atomic-vector." class="section level5">
<h5>One can give names to the elements of an atomic vector.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign names to a vector by specifying them
names(gene_expression) &lt;- c(&quot;ESR1&quot;, &quot;p53&quot;, &quot;PI3K&quot;, &quot;BRCA1&quot;, &quot;EGFR&quot;)
gene_expression</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  ESR1   p53  PI3K BRCA1  EGFR 
##     0   100    50   200    80</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># assign names to a vector using another vector
names(gene_expression) &lt;- gene_names
gene_expression</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  ESR1   p53  PI3K BRCA1  EGFR 
##     0   100    50   200    80</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="or-one-may-create-a-vector-with-named-elements-from-scratch." class="section level5">
<h5>Or One may create a vector with named elements from scratch.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_expression &lt;- c(ESR1=0, p53=100, PI3K=50, BRCA1=200, EGFR=80)
gene_expression</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  ESR1   p53  PI3K BRCA1  EGFR 
##     0   100    50   200    80</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="to-find-out-the-length-of-a-vector" class="section level5">
<h5>To find out the length of a vector:</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>length(gene_expression)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 5</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="note-a-vector-can-only-hold-elements-of-the-same-type.-if-there-are-a-mixture-of-data-types-they-will-be-coerced-according-to-the-coersion-rule-mentioned-earlier-in-this-documentation." class="section level5">
<h5><font color="red">NOTE: a vector can only hold elements of the same type. If there are a mixture of data types, they will be coerced according to the coersion rule mentioned earlier in this documentation.</font></h5>
<p><br></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="factors-a-factor-is-a-special-vector.-it-stores-categorical-data-which-are-important-in-statistical-modeling-and-can-only-take-on-a-limited-number-of-pre-defined-values.-the-function-factor-can-be-used-to-create-a-factor." class="section level4">
<h4>Factors: a factor is a special vector. It stores categorical data, which are important in statistical modeling and can only take on a limited number of pre-defined values. The function factor() can be used to create a factor.</h4>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>disease_stage &lt;- factor(c(&quot;Stage1&quot;, &quot;Stage2&quot;, &quot;Stage2&quot;, &quot;Stage3&quot;, &quot;Stage1&quot;, &quot;Stage4&quot;))
disease_stage</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] Stage1 Stage2 Stage2 Stage3 Stage1 Stage4
## Levels: Stage1 Stage2 Stage3 Stage4</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
<div id="in-r-categories-of-the-data-are-stored-as-factor-levels.-the-function-levels-can-be-used-to-access-the-factor-levels." class="section level5">
<h5>In R, categories of the data are stored as factor levels. The function levels() can be used to access the factor levels.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>levels(disease_stage)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Stage1&quot; &quot;Stage2&quot; &quot;Stage3&quot; &quot;Stage4&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="a-function-to-compactly-display-the-internal-structure-of-an-r-object-is-str.-please-use-str-to-display-the-internal-structure-of-the-object-we-just-created-disease_stage.-it-shows-that-disease_stage-is-a-factor-with-four-levels-stage1-stage2-stage3-etc-the-integer-numbers-after-the-colon-shows-that-these-levels-are-encoded-under-the-hood-by-integer-values-the-first-level-is-1-the-second-level-is-2-and-so-on.-basically-when-factor-function-is-called-r-first-scan-through-the-vector-to-determine-how-many-different-categories-there-are-then-it-converts-the-character-vector-to-a-vector-of-integer-values-with-each-integer-value-labeled-with-a-category." class="section level5">
<h5>A function to compactly display the internal structure of an R object is str(). Please use str() to display the internal structure of the object we just created <em>disease_stage</em>. It shows that <em>disease_stage</em> is a factor with four levels: “Stage1”, “Stage2”, “Stage3”, etc… The integer numbers after the colon shows that these levels are encoded under the hood by integer values: the first level is 1, the second level is 2, and so on. Basically, when <em>factor</em> function is called, R first scan through the vector to determine how many different categories there are, then it converts the character vector to a vector of integer values, with each integer value labeled with a category.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>str(disease_stage)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  Factor w/ 4 levels &quot;Stage1&quot;,&quot;Stage2&quot;,..: 1 2 2 3 1 4</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="by-default-r-infers-the-factor-levels-by-ordering-the-unique-elements-in-a-factor-alphanumerically.-one-may-specifically-define-the-factor-levels-at-the-creation-of-the-factor." class="section level5">
<h5>By default, R infers the factor levels by ordering the unique elements in a factor alphanumerically. One may specifically define the factor levels at the creation of the factor.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>disease_stage &lt;- factor(c(&quot;Stage1&quot;, &quot;Stage2&quot;, &quot;Stage2&quot;, &quot;Stage3&quot;, &quot;Stage1&quot;, &quot;Stage4&quot;), levels=c(&quot;Stage2&quot;, &quot;Stage1&quot;, &quot;Stage3&quot;, &quot;Stage4&quot;))
# The encoding for levels are different from above.
str(disease_stage)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  Factor w/ 4 levels &quot;Stage2&quot;,&quot;Stage1&quot;,..: 2 1 1 3 2 4</code></pre>
<p>If you want to know the number of individuals at each levels, there are two functions: <em>summary</em> and <em>table</em>.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>summary(disease_stage)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Stage2 Stage1 Stage3 Stage4 
##      2      2      1      1</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>table(disease_stage)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## disease_stage
## Stage2 Stage1 Stage3 Stage4 
##      2      2      1      1</code></pre>
</div>
</div>

<div id="matrices-a-matrix-is-like-an-excel-sheet-containing-multiple-rows-and-columns.-it-is-used-to-combine-vectors-of-the-same-type." class="section level4">
<h4>Matrices: A matrix is like an Excel sheet containing multiple rows and columns. It is used to combine vectors of the same type.</h4>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>col1 &lt;- c(1,3,8,9)
col2 &lt;- c(2,18,27,10)
col3 &lt;- c(8,37,267,19)

my_matrix &lt;- cbind(col1, col2, col3)
my_matrix</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      col1 col2 col3
## [1,]    1    2    8
## [2,]    3   18   37
## [3,]    8   27  267
## [4,]    9   10   19</code></pre>
<div id="one-other-way-to-create-a-matrix-is-to-use-matrix-function." class="section level5">
<h5>One other way to create a matrix is to use <em>matrix()</em> function.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>nums &lt;- c(col1, col2, col3)
nums</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  [1]   1   3   8   9   2  18  27  10   8  37 267  19</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>matrix(nums, ncol=2)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1   27
## [2,]    3   10
## [3,]    8    8
## [4,]    9   37
## [5,]    2  267
## [6,]   18   19</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>rownames(my_matrix) &lt;- c(&quot;row1&quot;, &quot;row2&quot;, &quot;row3&quot;, &quot;row4&quot;)
my_matrix</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      col1 col2 col3
## row1    1    2    8
## row2    3   18   37
## row3    8   27  267
## row4    9   10   19</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>t(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      row1 row2 row3 row4
## col1    1    3    8    9
## col2    2   18   27   10
## col3    8   37  267   19</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="to-find-out-the-dimension-of-a-matrix" class="section level5">
<h5>To find out the dimension of a matrix:</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>ncol(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 3</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>nrow(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 4</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>dim(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 4 3</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="calculations-with-numeric-matrices." class="section level5">
<h5>Calculations with numeric matrices.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_matrix * 3</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      col1 col2 col3
## row1    3    6   24
## row2    9   54  111
## row3   24   81  801
## row4   27   30   57</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>log10(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##           col1     col2     col3
## row1 0.0000000 0.301030 0.903090
## row2 0.4771213 1.255273 1.568202
## row3 0.9030900 1.431364 2.426511
## row4 0.9542425 1.000000 1.278754</code></pre>
<p>Total of each row.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>rowSums(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## row1 row2 row3 row4 
##   11   58  302   38</code></pre>
<p>Total of each column.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>colSums(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## col1 col2 col3 
##   21   57  331</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="there-is-a-data-structure-array-in-r-that-holds-multi-dimensional-d-2-data-and-is-a-generalized-version-of-a-matrix.-matrix-is-used-much-more-commonly-than-array-therefore-we-are-not-going-to-talk-about-array-here." class="section level5">
<h5>There is a data structure <em>Array</em> in R, that holds multi-dimensional (d &gt; 2) data and is a generalized version of a matrix. <em>Matrix</em> is used much more commonly than <em>Array</em>, therefore we are not going to talk about <em>Array</em> here.</h5>
</div>
</div>
<div id="data-frames-a-data-frame-is-like-a-matrix-but-can-have-columns-with-different-types-numeric-character-logical." class="section level4">
<h4>Data frames: a data frame is like a matrix but can have columns with different types (numeric, character, logical).</h4>
<div id="a-data-frame-can-be-created-using-the-function-data.frame." class="section level5">
<h5>A data frame can be created using the function data.frame().</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># creating a data frame using pre-defined vectors
patients_name=c(&quot;Patient1&quot;, &quot;Patient2&quot;, &quot;Patient3&quot;, &quot;Patient4&quot;, &quot;Patient5&quot;, &quot;Patient6&quot;)
Family_history=c(&quot;Y&quot;, &quot;N&quot;, &quot;Y&quot;, &quot;N&quot;, &quot;Y&quot;, &quot;Y&quot;)
patients_age=c(31, 40, 39, 50, 45, 65)
meta.data &lt;- data.frame(patients_name=patients_name, disease_stage=disease_stage, Family_history=Family_history, patients_age=patients_age)
meta.data</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65</code></pre>
<div id="to-check-whether-a-data-is-a-data-frame-use-the-function-is.data.frame." class="section level6">
<h6>To check whether a data is a data frame, use the function is.data.frame().</h6>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>is.data.frame(meta.data)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>is.data.frame(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] FALSE</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="one-can-convert-a-matrix-object-to-a-data-frame-using-the-function-as.data.frame." class="section level6">
<h6>One can convert a matrix object to a data frame using the function as.data.frame().</h6>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>class(my_matrix)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;matrix&quot; &quot;array&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_data &lt;- as.data.frame(my_matrix)
class(my_data)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;data.frame&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="a-data-frame-can-be-transposed-in-the-similar-way-as-a-matrix.-however-the-result-of-transposing-a-data-frame-might-not-be-a-data-frame-anymore." class="section level5">
<h5>A data frame can be transposed in the similar way as a matrix. However, the result of transposing a data frame might not be a data frame anymore.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_data</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      col1 col2 col3
## row1    1    2    8
## row2    3   18   37
## row3    8   27  267
## row4    9   10   19</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>t(my_data)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      row1 row2 row3 row4
## col1    1    3    8    9
## col2    2   18   27   10
## col3    8   37  267   19</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="a-data-frame-can-be-extended." class="section level5">
<h5>A data frame can be extended.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># add a column that has the information on harmful mutations in BRCA1/BRCA2 genes for each patient.
meta.data</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>meta.data$BRCA &lt;- c(&quot;YES&quot;, &quot;NO&quot;, &quot;YES&quot;, &quot;YES&quot;, &quot;YES&quot;, &quot;NO&quot;)
meta.data</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age BRCA
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31  YES
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40   NO
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39  YES
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50  YES
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45  YES
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65   NO</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="a-data-frame-can-also-be-extended-using-the-functions-cbind-and-rbind-for-adding-columns-and-rows-respectively.-when-using-cbind-the-number-of-values-in-the-new-column-must-match-the-number-of-rows-in-the-data-frame.-when-using-rbind-the-two-data-frames-must-have-the-same-variablescolumns." class="section level5">
<h5>A data frame can also be extended using the functions cbind() and rbind(), for adding columns and rows respectively. When using cbind(), the number of values in the new column must match the number of rows in the data frame. When using rbind(), the two data frames must have the same variables/columns.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># add a column that has the information on the racial information for each patient.
cbind(meta.data, Race=c(&quot;AJ&quot;, &quot;AS&quot;, &quot;AA&quot;, &quot;NE&quot;, &quot;NE&quot;, &quot;AS&quot;))</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age BRCA Race
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31  YES   AJ
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40   NO   AS
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39  YES   AA
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50  YES   NE
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45  YES   NE
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65   NO   AS</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># rbind can be used to add more rows to a data frame.
rbind(meta.data, data.frame(patients_name=&quot;Patient7&quot;, disease_stage=&quot;S4&quot;, Family_history=&quot;Y&quot;, patients_age=48, BRCA=&quot;YES&quot;))</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age BRCA
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31  YES
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40   NO
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39  YES
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50  YES
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45  YES
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65   NO
## 7      Patient7            S4              Y           48  YES</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="one-may-use-the-function-merge-to-merge-two-data-frames-horizontally-based-on-one-or-more-common-key-variables." class="section level5">
<h5>One may use the function <em>merge</em> to merge two data frames horizontally, based on one or more common key variables.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>expression.data &lt;- data.frame(patients_name=c(&quot;Patient3&quot;, &quot;Patient4&quot;, &quot;Patient5&quot;, &quot;Patient1&quot;, &quot;Patient2&quot;, &quot;Patient6&quot;), EGFR=c(10, 472, 103784, 1782, 187, 18289), TP53=c(16493, 72, 8193, 1849, 173894, 1482))
expression.data</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name   EGFR   TP53
## 1      Patient3     10  16493
## 2      Patient4    472     72
## 3      Patient5 103784   8193
## 4      Patient1   1782   1849
## 5      Patient2    187 173894
## 6      Patient6  18289   1482</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>md2 &lt;- merge(meta.data, expression.data, by=&quot;patients_name&quot;)
md2</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age BRCA   EGFR   TP53
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31  YES   1782   1849
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40   NO    187 173894
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39  YES     10  16493
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50  YES    472     72
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45  YES 103784   8193
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65   NO  18289   1482</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="lists-a-list-is-an-ordered-collection-of-objects-which-can-be-any-type-of-r-objects-vectors-matrices-data-frames-even-lists." class="section level4">
<h4>Lists: a list is an ordered collection of objects, which can be any type of R objects (vectors, matrices, data frames, even lists).</h4>
<div id="a-list-is-constructed-using-the-function-list." class="section level5">
<h5>A list is constructed using the function list().</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_list &lt;- list(1:5, &quot;a&quot;, c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE), c(3.2, 103.0, 82.3))
my_list</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] &quot;a&quot;
## 
## [[3]]
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE
## 
## [[4]]
## [1]   3.2 103.0  82.3</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>str(my_list)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## List of 4
##  $ : int [1:5] 1 2 3 4 5
##  $ : chr &quot;a&quot;
##  $ : logi [1:3] TRUE FALSE FALSE
##  $ : num [1:3] 3.2 103 82.3</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="one-could-construct-a-list-by-giving-names-to-elements." class="section level5">
<h5>One could construct a list by giving names to elements.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_list &lt;- list(Ranking=1:5, ID=&quot;a&quot;, Test=c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE), Score=c(3.2, 103.0, 82.3))

# display the names of elements in the list using the function *names*, or *str*. Compare the output of *str* with the above results to see the difference.
names(my_list)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Ranking&quot; &quot;ID&quot;      &quot;Test&quot;    &quot;Score&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>str(my_list)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## List of 4
##  $ Ranking: int [1:5] 1 2 3 4 5
##  $ ID     : chr &quot;a&quot;
##  $ Test   : logi [1:3] TRUE FALSE FALSE
##  $ Score  : num [1:3] 3.2 103 82.3</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># number of elements in the list
length(my_list)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 4</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="subsetting-data" class="section level4">
<h4>Subsetting data</h4>
</div>
<div id="subsetting-allows-one-to-access-the-piece-of-data-of-interest.-when-combinded-with-assignment-subsetting-can-modify-selected-pieces-of-data.-the-operators-that-can-be-used-to-subset-data-are-and-." class="section level4">
<h4>Subsetting allows one to access the piece of data of interest. When combinded with assignment, subsetting can modify selected pieces of data. The operators that can be used to subset data are: [, $, and [[.</h4>
<div id="first-we-are-going-to-talk-about-subsetting-data-using-which-is-the-most-commonly-used-operator.-we-will-start-by-looking-at-vectors-and-talk-about-four-ways-to-subset-a-vector." class="section level5">
<h5>First, we are going to talk about subsetting data using [, which is the most commonly used operator. We will start by looking at vectors and talk about four ways to subset a vector.</h5>
<ul>
<li><font color="purple"><strong>Positive integers</strong> return elements at the specified positions</font></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># first to recall what are stored in gene_names
gene_names</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot;  &quot;p53&quot;   &quot;PI3K&quot;  &quot;BRCA1&quot; &quot;EGFR&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># obtain the first and the third elements
gene_names[c(1,3)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot; &quot;PI3K&quot;</code></pre>
<p>R uses 1 based indexing, meaning the first element is at the position 1, not at position 0.</p>
<ul>
<li><font color="purple"><strong>Negative integers</strong> omit elements at the specified positions</font></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names[-c(1,3)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;p53&quot;   &quot;BRCA1&quot; &quot;EGFR&quot;</code></pre>
<p>One may not mixed positive and negative integers in one single subset operation.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># The following command will produce an error.
gene_names[c(-1, 2)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Error in gene_names[c(-1, 2)]: only 0's may be mixed with negative subscripts</code></pre>
<ul>
<li><font color="purple"><strong>Logical vectors</strong> select elements where the corresponding logical value is TRUE</font>, This is very useful because one may write the expression that creates the logical vector.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names[c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot; &quot;PI3K&quot;</code></pre>
<p>Recall that we have created one vector called <em>gene_expression</em>. Let’s assume that <em>gene_expression</em> stores the expression values correspond to the genes in <em>gene_names</em>. Then we may subset the genes based on expression values.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_expression</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  ESR1   p53  PI3K BRCA1  EGFR 
##     0   100    50   200    80</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names[gene_expression &gt; 50]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;p53&quot;   &quot;BRCA1&quot; &quot;EGFR&quot;</code></pre>
<p>If the logical vector is shorter in length than the data vector that we want to subset, then it will be recycled to be the same length as the data vector.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names[c(TRUE, FALSE)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot; &quot;PI3K&quot; &quot;EGFR&quot;</code></pre>
<p>If the logical vector has “NA” in it, the corresponding value will be “NA” in the output. “NA” in R is a sysmbol for missing value.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names[c(TRUE, NA, FALSE, TRUE, NA)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot;  NA      &quot;BRCA1&quot; NA</code></pre>
<ul>
<li><font color="purple"><strong>Character vectors</strong> return elements with matching names, when the vector is named.</font></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_expression</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  ESR1   p53  PI3K BRCA1  EGFR 
##     0   100    50   200    80</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_expression[c(&quot;ESR1&quot;, &quot;p53&quot;)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## ESR1  p53 
##    0  100</code></pre>
<ul>
<li><font color="purple"><strong>Nothing</strong> returns the original vector</font>, This is more useful for matrices, data frames than for vectors.</li>
</ul>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>gene_names[]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;ESR1&quot;  &quot;p53&quot;   &quot;PI3K&quot;  &quot;BRCA1&quot; &quot;EGFR&quot;</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="subsetting-a-list-works-in-the-same-way-as-subsetting-an-atomic-vector.-using-will-always-return-a-list." class="section level5">
<h5>Subsetting a list works in the same way as subsetting an atomic vector. Using [ will always return a list.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_list[1]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## $Ranking
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="subsetting-a-matrix-can-be-done-by-simply-generalizing-the-one-dimension-subsetting-one-may-supply-a-one-dimension-index-for-each-dimension-of-the-matrix.-blanknothing-subsetting-is-now-useful-in-keeping-all-rows-or-all-columns." class="section level5">
<h5>Subsetting a matrix can be done by simply generalizing the one dimension subsetting: one may supply a one dimension index for each dimension of the matrix. <font color="red">Blank/Nothing subsetting is now useful in keeping all rows or all columns.</font></h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_matrix[c(TRUE, FALSE), ]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      col1 col2 col3
## row1    1    2    8
## row3    8   27  267</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="subsetting-a-data-frame-can-be-done-similarly-as-subsetting-a-matrix.-in-addition-one-may-supply-only-one-1-dimensional-index-to-subset-a-data-frame.-in-this-case-r-will-treat-the-data-frame-as-a-list-with-each-column-is-an-element-in-the-list." class="section level5">
<h5>Subsetting a data frame can be done similarly as subsetting a matrix. In addition, one may supply only one 1-dimensional index to subset a data frame. In this case, R will treat the data frame as a list with each column is an element in the list.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># recall a data frame created from above: *meta.data*
meta.data</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age BRCA
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31  YES
## 2      Patient2        Stage2              N           40   NO
## 3      Patient3        Stage2              Y           39  YES
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50  YES
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45  YES
## 6      Patient6        Stage4              Y           65   NO</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># subset the data frame similarly to a matrix
meta.data[c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE),]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_name disease_stage Family_history patients_age BRCA
## 1      Patient1        Stage1              Y           31  YES
## 4      Patient4        Stage3              N           50  YES
## 5      Patient5        Stage1              Y           45  YES</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># subset the data frame using one vector
meta.data[c(&quot;patients_age&quot;, &quot;disease_stage&quot;)]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   patients_age disease_stage
## 1           31        Stage1
## 2           40        Stage2
## 3           39        Stage2
## 4           50        Stage3
## 5           45        Stage1
## 6           65        Stage4</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="subsetting-operators-and" class="section level4">
<h4>Subsetting operators: <strong>[[</strong> and <strong>$</strong></h4>
<div id="is-similar-to-except-that-it-returns-the-content-of-the-element." class="section level5">
<h5><strong>[[</strong> is similar to <strong>[</strong>, except that it returns the content of the element.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># recall my_list
my_list</code></pre>
<pre><code>## $Ranking
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
## 
## $ID
## [1] &quot;a&quot;
## 
## $Test
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE
## 
## $Score
## [1]   3.2 103.0  82.3</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># comparing [[ with [ in subsetting a list
my_list[[1]]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my_list[1]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## $Ranking
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
<p><font color="red">[[ is very useful when working with a list. Because when [ is applied to a list, it always returns a list. While [[ returns the contents of the list. [[ can only extrac/return one element, so it only accept one integer/string as input.</font></p>
<p>Because data frames are implemented as lists of columns, one may use [[ to extract a column from data frames.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>meta.data[[&quot;disease_stage&quot;]]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] Stage1 Stage2 Stage2 Stage3 Stage1 Stage4
## Levels: Stage2 Stage1 Stage3 Stage4</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="is-a-shorthand-for-combined-with-character-subsetting." class="section level5">
<h5><strong>$</strong> is a shorthand for <strong>[[</strong> combined with character subsetting.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># subsetting a list using $ 
my_list$Score</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]   3.2 103.0  82.3</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># subsetting a data frame using
meta.data$disease_stage</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] Stage1 Stage2 Stage2 Stage3 Stage1 Stage4
## Levels: Stage2 Stage1 Stage3 Stage4</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="simplifying-vs.preserving-subsetting" class="section level5">
<h5>Simplifying vs. preserving subsetting</h5>
<p>We have seen some examples of simplying vs. preserving subsetting, for example:</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># simplifying subsetting
my_list[[1]]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># preserving subsetting
my_list[1]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## $Ranking
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
<p>Basically, simplying subsetting returns the simplest possible data structure that can represent the output. While preserving subsetting keeps the structure of the output as the same as the input. In the above example, [[ simplifies the output to a vector, while [ keeps the output as a list.</p>
<p>Because the syntax of carrying out simplifying and preserving subsetting differs depending on the data structure, the table below provides the information for the most basic data structure.</p>
<table class="table table-striped" style="width: auto !important; ">
<thead>
<tr>
<th style="text-align:left;">
</th>
<th style="text-align:center;">
Simplifying
</th>
<th style="text-align:center;">
Preserving
</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="text-align:left;">
Vector
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[[1]]
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[1]
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="text-align:left;">
List
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[[1]]
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[1]
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="text-align:left;">
Factor
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[1:3, drop=T]
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[1:3]
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="text-align:left;">
Data frame
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[, 1] or x[[1]]
</td>
<td style="text-align:center;">
x[, 1, drop=F] or x[1]
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><font color="blue">Please play around with the data structures that we have created to understand the behaviours of simplifying and preserving subsetting</font></p>
<hr />
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="topic-3.-import-and-export-data-in-r" class="section level1">
<h1>Topic 3. Import and export data in R</h1>
<div id="r-base-function-read.table-is-a-general-funciton-that-can-be-used-to-read-a-file-in-table-format.-the-data-will-be-imported-as-a-data-frame." class="section level5">
<h5>R base function read.table() is a general funciton that can be used to read a file in table format. The data will be imported as a data frame.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># There is a very convenient way to read files from the internet.
data1 &lt;- read.table(file=&quot;https://github.com/ucdavis-bioinformatics-training/courses/raw/master/Intro2R/raw_counts.txt&quot;, sep=&quot;\t&quot;, header=T, stringsAsFactors=F)

# To read a local file. If you have downloaded the raw_counts.txt file to your local machine, you may use the following command to read it in, by providing the full path for the file location. The way to specify the full path is the same as taught in the command line session.
download.file(&quot;https://github.com/ucdavis-bioinformatics-training/courses/raw/master/Intro2R/raw_counts.txt&quot;, &quot;./raw_counts.txt&quot;)
data1 &lt;- read.table(file=&quot;./raw_counts.txt&quot;, sep=&quot;\t&quot;, header=T, stringsAsFactors=F)</code></pre>
<p>To check what type of object <em>data1</em> is in and take a look at the beginning part of the data.</p>

<div id="depending-on-the-format-of-the-file-several-variants-of-read.table-are-available-to-make-reading-a-file-easier." class="section level5">
<h5>Depending on the format of the file, several variants of read.table() are available to make reading a file easier.</h5>
<ul>
<li><p>read.csv(): for reading “comma separated value” files (.csv).</p></li>
<li><p>read.csv2(): variant used in countries that use a comma “,” as decimal point and a semicolon “;” as field separators.</p></li>
<li><p>read.delim(): for reading “tab separated value” files (“.txt”). By default, point(“.”) is used as decimal point.</p></li>
<li><p>read.delim2(): for reading “tab separated value” files (“.txt”). By default, comma (“,”) is used as decimal point.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># We are going to read a file over the internet by providing the url of the file.
data2 &lt;- read.csv(file=&quot;https://github.com/ucdavis-bioinformatics-training/courses/raw/master/Intro2R/raw_counts.csv&quot;, stringsAsFactors=F)

# To look at the file:
head(data2)</code></pre>

<div id="r-base-function-write.table-can-be-used-to-export-data-to-a-file." class="section level5">
<h5>R base function write.table() can be used to export data to a file.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># To write to a file called &quot;output.txt&quot; in your current working directory.
write.table(data2[1:20,], file=&quot;output.txt&quot;, sep=&quot;\t&quot;, quote=F, row.names=T, col.names=T)</code></pre>
<p>It is also possible to export data to a csv file.</p>
<p>write.csv()</p>

<div id="conditional-structure" class="section level4">
<h4>Conditional structure</h4>
<p>Decision making is important in programming. This can be achieved using an <strong>if…else</strong> statement.</p>
<p>The basic structure of an <em>if…else</em> statement is</p>
<p><strong>if (condition statement){</strong></p>
<p><strong>some operation</strong></p>
<p><strong>}</strong></p>
<p>Two examples of <em>if…else</em> statement</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>Temperature &lt;- 30

if (Temperature &lt; 32){
  print(&quot;Very cold&quot;)
}</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Very cold&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># recall gene_expression, we are going to design a *if...else* statement to decide treatment plans based on gene expression.

if (gene_expression[&quot;ESR1&quot;] &gt; 0){
  print(&quot;Treatment plan 1&quot;)
}else if(gene_expression[&quot;BRCA1&quot;] &gt; 0){
  print(&quot;Treatment plan 2&quot;)
}else if(gene_expression[&quot;p53&quot;] &gt; 0){
  print(&quot;Treatment plan 3&quot;)
}else{
  print(&quot;Treatment plan 4&quot;)
}</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Treatment plan 2&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="loop-structure" class="section level4">
<h4>Loop structure</h4>
<p>In programming, it is common that one has to do one set of specific operation on a sequence of elements. In this case, <em>for</em> loop is very useful to achieve the goal.</p>
<p>The basic structure of <em>for</em> loop is:</p>
<p><strong>for (value in sequence){</strong></p>
<p><strong>some operation</strong></p>
<p><strong>}</strong></p>
<p>For example, we would like to calculate the sum of a row for every row in the matrix we created earlier. We are going to use a <em>for</em> loop to do it.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>for (i in 1:dim(my_matrix)[1]){
  out &lt;- sum(my_matrix[i, ])
  print(out)
}</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 11
## [1] 58
## [1] 302
## [1] 38</code></pre>
<p>There is a <strong>while</strong> loop in R similarly as in command line or any other programming language. The basic structure of a <em>while</em> loop is:</p>
<p><strong>while (condition){</strong></p>
<p><strong>some operation</strong></p>
<p><strong>}</strong></p>
<div id="challenge" class="section level5">
<h5><font color="blue">Challenge:</font></h5>
<p>Please rewrite the calculation of the column sum using <em>while</em> loop.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="solution" class="section level4">
<h4><font color="skyblue">Solution:</font></h4>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>while (i &lt;= dim(my_matrix)[1]){
  out &lt;- sum(my_matrix[i,])
  print(out)
  i &lt;- i + 1
}</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 38</code></pre>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="a-few-useful-functions-apply-lapply-sapply-and-tapply-to-replace-for-loop" class="section level4">
<h4>A few useful functions: apply(), lapply(), sapply(), and tapply() to replace for loop</h4>
<div id="apply-takes-array-or-matrix-as-input-and-output-in-vector-array-or-list." class="section level5">
<h5>apply() takes array or matrix as input and output in vector, array or list.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># recall my_matrix
my_matrix</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      col1 col2 col3
## row1    1    2    8
## row2    3   18   37
## row3    8   27  267
## row4    9   10   19</code></pre>
<pre class="r colsel"><code># check the usage of apply() function

apply(my_matrix, MARGIN=1, sum)</code></pre>

<div id="the-function-sapply-works-like-function-lapply-but-tries-to-simplify-the-output-to-the-most-elementary-data-structure-that-is-possible.-as-a-matter-of-fact-sapply-is-a-wrapper-function-for-lapply.-by-default-it-returns-a-vector." class="section level5">
<h5>The function sapply() works like function lapply(), but tries to simplify the output to the most elementary data structure that is possible. As a matter of fact, sapply() is a “wrapper” function for lapply(). By default, it returns a vector.</h5>

<div id="the-function-tapply-applys-a-function-to-each-subset-of-a-vector-based-on-a-second-vector-of-factors." class="section level4">
<h4>The function tapply() applys a function to each subset of a vector based on a second vector of factors.</h4>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>?tapply()

# Let's use Fisher's Iris data to demonstrate the usage of tapply().

<div id="write-ones-own-functions" class="section level4">
<h4>Write one’s own functions</h4>
<p>Even though there are a lot of R packages available, there are always situations where one might have to write one’s own function to accomplish some very specific goals. Functions are defined by code with a specific format:</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>function.name &lt;- function(arg1=arg1, arg2, ...){
    var &lt;- sin(arg1) + sin(arg2)  # carry out tasks
    var / 2
}</code></pre>
<p>Here, we are going to write a function to calculate the area of a triangle given the lengths of three sides.</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>my.area &lt;- function(side1=side1, side2=side2, side3=side3){
    circumference &lt;- (side1 + side2 + side3) / 2
    area &lt;- sqrt(circumference * (circumference - side1) * (circumference - side2) * (circumference - side3))
    return(area)
}

# let's carry out some test
my.area(side1=3, side2=4, side3=5)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 6</code></pre>
<p><br></p>

<div id="topic-6.-simple-data-visulization-in-r" class="section level1">
<h1>Topic 6. Simple data visulization in R</h1>
<p>Scatter plot and line plot can be produced using the function plot().</p>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>x &lt;- c(1:50)

<div id="topic-7.-install-packages-in-r" class="section level1">
<h1>Topic 7. Install packages in R</h1>
<div id="starting-from-bioconductor-version-3.8-the-installation-of-packages-is-recommended-to-use-biocmanager." class="section level5">
<h5>Starting from Bioconductor version 3.8, the installation of packages is recommended to use BiocManager.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>if (!requireNamespace(&quot;BiocManager&quot;))
    install.packages(&quot;BiocManager&quot;)
## install core packages
BiocManager::install()
## install specific packages
BiocManager::install(c(&quot;devtools&quot;, &quot;tidyverse&quot;,&quot;bsseq&quot;,&quot;DSS&quot;))</code></pre>
<ul>
<li><p>Bioconductor has a repository and release schedule that differ from R (Bioconductor has a ‘devel’ branch to which new packages and updates are introduced, and a stable ‘release’ branch emitted once every 6 months to which bug fixes but not new features are introduced). This mismatch causes that the version detected by install.packages() is sometimes not the most recent ‘release’.</p></li>
<li><p>A consequence of the distinct ‘devel’ branch is that install.packages() sometimes points only to the ‘release’ repository, while users might want to have access to the leading-edge features in the develop version.</p></li>
<li><p>An indirect consequence of Bioconductor’s structured release is that packages generally have more extensive dependences with one another.</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="it-is-always-recommended-to-update-to-the-most-current-version-of-r-and-bioconductor.-if-it-is-not-possible-and-r-3.5.0-please-use-the-legacy-approach-to-install-bioconductor-packages" class="section level5">
<h5><font color="orange">It is always recommended to update to the most current version of R and Bioconductor. If it is not possible and R &lt; 3.5.0, please use the legacy approach to install Bioconductor packages</font></h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>source(&quot;http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R&quot;)
## install core packages
biocLite()
## install specific packages
biocLite(c(&quot;devtools&quot;, &quot;tidyverse&quot;,&quot;bsseq&quot;,&quot;DSS&quot;))</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="the-r-function-install.packages-can-be-used-to-install-packages-that-are-not-part-of-bioconductor." class="section level5">
<h5>The R function install.packages() can be used to install packages that are not part of Bioconductor.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>install.packages(&quot;ggplot2&quot;, repos=&quot;http://cran.us.r-project.org&quot;)
install.packages(c(&quot;kableExtra&quot;,&quot;knitr&quot;,&quot;dplyr&quot;))</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="install-from-source-of-github." class="section level5">
<h5>Install from source of github.</h5>
<pre class="r colsel"><code>library(devtools)
install_github(&quot;stephenturner/qqman&quot;)</code></pre>

<div id="topic-9.-r-markdown-and-r-notebooks" class="section level1">
<h1>Topic 9. R markdown and R notebooks</h1>
<p>Markdown is a system that allow easy incorporation of annotations/comments together with computing code. Both the raw source of markdown file and the rendered output are easy to read. R markdown allows both interactive mode with R and producing a reproducible document. An R notebook is an R markdown document with code chunks that can be executed independently and interactively, with output visible immediately beneath the input. In RStudio, by default, all R markdown documents are run in R notebook mode. Under the R notebook mode, when executing a chunk, the code is sent to the console to be run one line at a time. This allows execution to stop if a line raises an error.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>In RStudio, creating an R notebook can be done by going to the menu command ** File -&gt; New File -&gt; R Notebook **.</p>
<p>An example of an R notebook looks like:</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<p>The way to run the R code inside the code chunk is to use the green arrow located at the top right corner of each of the code chunk, or use ** Ctrl + Shift + Enter ** on Windows, or ** Cmd + Shift + Enter ** on Mac to run the current code chunk. To run each individual code line, one uses ** Ctrl + Enter ** on Windows, or ** Cmd + Enter ** on Mac.</p>
<p>To render R notebook to html/pdf/word documents can be done using the <strong>Preview</strong> menu.</p>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
